Abstract
Reservoir Computing is a machine learning model that is fast to train and has been
successfully employed to process both temporal data and spatio-temporal data. In this
report I will look at many of the capabilities and applications of Reservoir Computing.
I will ﬁrst look at how it was used to explore data generated by nonlinear partial diﬀer-
ential equations. Multiple tests and plots allow us to understand and learn more about
the data and the way the artiﬁcial intelligence model works. I investigate diﬀerent ways
of making predictions and how to improve the accuracy and performance. This research
can help other scientists learn more about the usage of Reservoir Computing. By feed-
ing the model real crime data, the Reservoir Computer is used to generate information
on criminal activity in the Washington DC area. Some of the critical aspects of this
research include the preprocessing and smoothing of quantitative criminal activity data
and Observation - predicting the times and locations of one crime (ex: homicides) using
the data of another crime (ex: robberies). This can help law enforcement know where
to look for evidence on past homicides. The code developed during this program could
be very beneﬁcial to people and entities who have strong data sets.

1 Introduction: Reservoir computing
Reservoir Computing (RC) is a dynamic machine learning model. It is a type of recurrent
neural network, valuable for processing spatial temporal data. Its application in criminal
data analysis holds promise, as RC captures complex patterns and temporal relationships,
leading to improved crime prediction, hotspot identiﬁcation, and informed decision-making
for law enforcement and policymakers, ultimately aligning with the Department of Homeland
Security’s mission.
All the programming during this research project was done using the software MATLAB. In
the programming code, the RC is represented as a matrix. In the equations it will be called
(Ω). The RC is created by a function called ”LeakyTanhMapFunc”. The function takes in 4
inputs: α, A0, W, and the drive signal.
αis the leakage parameter, it ranges from 0 to 1. During the construction of the RC, α
serves as a setting to control the level of impact each previous state of the reservoir has on
the current state of the reservoir. For our model, α= 0.1 has been our choice because it
yields the smallest testing and training errors.
A0 is the adjacency matrix that represents the connectivity pattern of the reservoir’s nodes.
In our implementation of the reservoir computer, A0 is generated using the Erd˝os-R´enyi (ER)
model with a connection probability of 0.01. The ER model randomly assigns connections
between nodes based on the given probability.
W is a vector of randomly initialized coeﬃcients between -1 and 1 that represents the nodes
of the reservoir.
The drive signal, is the input data. It determines the states of the RC which will be able to
make estimations on a diﬀerent data set that evolves in time with the drive data set.
The LeakyTanhMap function iteratively updates the reservoir state by combining the previ-
ous state with the input signal using the leaky tanh map equation. The reservoir states are
stored as rows in the matrix ρ, which represents the reservoir computer. [1]
The task given to the reservoir computer is called ”observation”, which is predicting the evo-
lution of data set 1 based on the relative evolution of data set 2 in time. I start by applying
this to the Lorenz system, to predict one variable from the system of equations using the
other. The Lorenz system is a set of diﬀerential equations that exempliﬁes chaotic behavior
and sensitivity to initial conditions, often used to illustrate the concept of chaos theory. It
has three variables that evolve in time, which makes it useful for practicing machine learning.
For example, I give the RC the task of predicting y given x and choose the time span to be
15000. Given the correct initial conditions, the Lorenz system produces the Lorenz attractor.
I then save the data that it produces from t = 1, to t = 15000. This gives us 15000 sets of
x,y, and z scalars (3 column vectors x,y, and zof length 15000). One of the vector variables
is used as the input (drive signal), one is used as the output to be predicted, and one is
disregarded. I will select xas the input signal and zas the output signal.
Both the reservoir computer matrix ρ, and the vector variables have a number of rows equal
to the time span. The value is 15000 in our case. To separate training phase and the testing
phase, a training index is chosen. Let it be 10000. The ﬁrst 10000 rows of ρbecome the
matrix Ω, and the other 5000 rows become the matrix Ω. Ω is used for training and Ω is
3
used for testing. The same is done for the output signal z, from which I obtain the training
signal gtr and the testing signal gte.
2 Comparing two diﬀerent approaches
I am using data generated by the Lorenz system of ordinary diﬀerential equations to mimic
crime data that is only temporal. The results are from observation (predicting one data set
oﬀ of the other).
2.1 Pseudo-inverse method (Kappa)
The variable κis the product of the pseudo inverse of Ω and the training signal gtr . The
predicted signals ﬁt train signal ftr and ﬁt test signal fte are then computed using kappa
as you can see below. This technique has given us the strongest predictions so far, with the
smallest errors. Ω and Ω represent the matrix for the RC, from which a portion of the matrix
is used for training and the other for testing.

2.2 Pearson Correlations method
For this technique, I computed the Pearson correlations between the readouts from Ω (the
reservoir computer training portion) and the expected output for training. The readouts
correspond to what each node is producing. Each node readout is a column from Ω. The
4
correlations were stored in the form of a column vector (we’ll call it C) with each value cor-
responding to the correlation between one readout (Ri, from Ω) and the expected training
output signal (gtr ).
The correlations C were then used to estimate the output signal, ﬁt train signal (ftr ):

2.4 Trade-oﬀ of computing and using Pearson Coeﬃcients as op-
posed to the pseudo inverse of Omega:
PROS:
•Computing the Pearson Coeﬃcients does not involve ﬁnding the inverse of Omega and
storing it. Doing this takes more time and more storage. The Pearson technique is
therefore less computationally taxing.
6
•Correlations can be computed individually of each other, unlike the kappas, which is
one operation. Therefore, multiple machines can be used to do the task of computing
the Pearson Coeﬃcients.
CONS:
•The Pearson Correlations technique is much less accurate than the Pseudo inverse one
as you can see in the error comparison tables in section 2.3.
3 Exploring the Kuramoto Sivashinski system of dif-
ferential equations through reservoir computing
The Kuramoto-Sivashinsky equation is a partial diﬀerential equation that describes the be-
havior of spatially extended systems displaying complex patterns and turbulence, often ob-
served in various physical and chemical systems. It is a nonlinear evolution equation with
applications in ﬂuid dynamics, combustion, and pattern formation.
I am using the data that it generates to imitate spatiotemporal crime data and apply obser-
vation using the reservoir computer.
3.1 Plotting the errors against the distance from the drive signal
(Kuramoto Sivashinski)
I ﬁrst choose a variable to be the drive signal. Starting with the closest neighboring variable
as the target, I iterate through, each time predicting a dimension further than the last, and
I register the errors. In the following plots, I look at how the distance of the target variable
from the drive variable aﬀects the accuracy (the errors) of the prediction. For each distance
(1 to 32), there is an error for the distance to the right of the variable, and an error for the
distance to the left of it. For example, both dimensions 64 and 2 are considered to be at the
same distance from dimension 1. Conclusion: As the distance between the drive variable and
the target variable increases, the accuracy of observation decreases.
7
Figure 4: Both methods - testing
3.2 Driving the reservoir with multiple variables
In search of an optimal driver for the reservoir, I did the following.
Using neighboring variables on both sides as drive: starting with only the two immediate
neighbors as the drive, I continuously expanded the span of drive signals. For example if
variable 10 was the target signal, I would iterate by ﬁrst using variable 9 and 11 as drive,
then 8,9,11,12, then 7,8,9,11,12,13 and so on. Using variables on the left side as drive: I only
take into consideration the variables on the left. Example: if 10 was the target, I would start
by using 9 as the drive, then 8,9, then 7,8,9 and so on. Using variables on the right: same as
left but only right variables.
Out of these three options, the most accurate was using neighboring variables on both sides,
as expected, because it is more information and insight on how the target variables behave
relative to the neighboring variables.
From the plots, I notice a trend that when the span is 5 variables, the errors are smallest.
Conclusion: Optimal span for drive signal in the KS system is 5 variables.

as the drive signal
4 Applying Reservoir Computing Observation to crime
data
The term ”observation” speciﬁcally refers to the collection or extraction of information from
the evolving state of the reservoir as it responds to input data. This information can be
analyzed and used for various tasks, such as making predictions, classiﬁcations, or generating
patterns.
In the context of crime analysis, I am observing and utilizing the reservoir’s dynamic state
to make predictions or gain insights about criminal activity, such as predicting the times and
locations of one type of crime based on the data of another type of crime. This process involves
extracting meaningful information from the reservoir’s evolving internal representation of the
data.
4.1 Only temporal dimension
Washington DC crime incidents in 2016, open data. [2] Time span: year of 2016 (it’s a leap
year so there are 366 timestamps)
Location: DC area
After cleaning and processing the data:
Description of the cleaned data: 365 x 25 matrix (365 rows, 25 columns). Each column
represents a crime, and each row represents a day from the year of 2016. The value in each
cell is the number of times the speciﬁed crime was reported on the speciﬁed day. For example:
the number in row 20, column 1, is the number of robberies committed on the 20th day of
2016.

4.2 Spatial and temporal dimensions
To incorporate the spatial aspect into the observation, the data needed to be reorganized.
Using latitude and longitude, the DC area was divided into roughly 400 zones. For the data,
each crime was assigned 366 grids. Each of these matrices represented the crime data for one
day. Each cell of the matrix represents a spatial zone in the dc area. The contents of a cell
represent the number of crimes committed on a given day in that zone.
Here is an example of the what a portion of a spatial grid looks like.
Figure 7: Portion of raw spatial grid for robberies committed on the ﬁrst day of 2016 in the
DC area
This data does not really give much valuable information because it is raw and contains
a lot of noise. The reservoir computer does not behave very well with data in this form (raw
data). To ﬁx this, I smoothed the data:
I manually implemented a circular smoothing technique to reﬁne the data. By averaging
the values within a circular region around each data point, variations and noise are reduced,
revealing clearer patterns and trends in the dataset. The radius of the circular region is
adjustable, to increase or decrease the smoothing.
For every data point, the code calculates a weighted sum of values within this circular
region. The weight assigned to each neighboring point decreases as its distance from the
11
center of the circle increases. This weight-based approach ensures that closer points have a
stronger inﬂuence on the smoothed value.
The calculated weighted sum is then divided by the total accumulated weight to obtain the
smoothed value for the central data point. This smoothing operation eﬀectively mitigates
noise and small-scale variations in the data by replacing each data point with a weighted
average of its neighbors. As a result, the overall trends and patterns within the dataset
become more prominent and easier to analyze, aiding in the extraction of meaningful insights.
This process helps enhance the overall interpretability and analysis of the data.
Figure 8: Portion of smoothed spatial grid for robberies committed on the ﬁrst day of 2016
in the DC area
Figure 9: Image comparison of smoothed data vs raw data.
For a given crime, there is a smoothed ”image” for each day representing the locations
of incidents on that day of the year. With 366 images, I had to ﬁgure out how these images
could be fed into the RC, taking into consideration the spatial nature of the data.
12
Since the RC operates on a time-series basis, it needed to be fed one image per timestamp
(day). So, I transformed each image into a long vector by setting the rows next to each other.
I then stacked these vectors onto each other forming one large matrix for a given crime, with
366 rows, each row being a reorganized image. Here is a simpliﬁed visual representation:

Example of the applications that this could have for the DHS
By feeding the RC 365 days of robbery data, and 200 days of homicide data (training phase),
the RC will learn the underlying correlation between the two crimes. This will then allow it
to predict the days and locations of homicides for the last 165 days. Thus, providing valuable
leads for law enforcement on where to search for homicide evidence.
